4. Death Check
Monitors if a philosopher has died.

check_death(data) â†’ Thread responsible for detecting deaths.
monitor_philosopher_death(data) â†’ Iterates through philosophers to check if any have died.
has_died(philo) â†’ Determines if a philosopher has exceeded time_to_die.
should_stop_monitoring(data) â†’ Checks if the simulation should stop.

ğŸ“Œ Ensures a philosopherâ€™s death is detected immediately.
ğŸ“„ Files: monitor_death.câ€‹monitor_death, simulation.câ€‹simulation

5. Printing of Messages
Handles the output of messages to prevent race conditions.

print_msg(philo, msg) â†’ Displays philosopher actions (eating, sleeping, thinking, taking forks, dying).
get_time_ms() â†’ Returns the current timestamp in milliseconds.

ğŸ“Œ Ensures that messages are printed correctly without overlapping.
ğŸ“„ File: tools.câ€‹tools

6. Freeing/Cleaning/Closing
Properly releases allocated memory and destroys mutexes.

free_philo_mutexes(data) â†’ Destroys individual mutexes for philosophers.
free_global_mutexes(data) â†’ Destroys global mutexes (print, death locks).
free_data(data) â†’ Frees all allocated memory.
close_adm(data, str) â†’ Calls cleanup functions and prints exit message.
ğŸ“Œ Prevents memory leaks and ensures proper cleanup at program termination.
ğŸ“„ File: cleaning.câ€‹cleaning

7. General Workflow Summary
Validate input.
Initialize structures, forks, and threads.
Start philosopher threads.
Each philosopher alternates between eating, sleeping, and thinking.
Monitoring threads check if a philosopher has died or if all have eaten enough.
If a philosopher dies, the simulation stops immediately.
Clean up resources before exiting.
ğŸ“Œ Manages the overall flow of execution to ensure proper simulation behavior.
ğŸ“„ File: main.câ€‹

